Regression Project: Boston House Price Prediction¶

¶

Welcome to the project on regression. We will use the Boston house price dataset for this project.

Objective¶

The problem at hand is to predict the housing prices of a town or a suburb based on the features of the locality provided to us. In the process, we need to identify the most important features affecting the price of the house. We need to employ techniques of data preprocessing and build a linear regression model that predicts the prices for the unseen data.

Dataset¶

Each record in the database describes a house in Boston suburb or town. The data was drawn from the Boston Standard Metropolitan Statistical Area (SMSA) in 1970. Detailed attribute information can be found below:

Attribute Information:

  • CRIM: Per capita crime rate by town
  • ZN: Proportion of residential land zoned for lots over 25,000 sq.ft.
  • INDUS: Proportion of non-retail business acres per town
  • CHAS: Charles River dummy variable (= 1 if tract bounds river; 0 otherwise)
  • NOX: Nitric Oxide concentration (parts per 10 million)
  • RM: The average number of rooms per dwelling
  • AGE: Proportion of owner-occupied units built before 1940
  • DIS: Weighted distances to five Boston employment centers
  • RAD: Index of accessibility to radial highways
  • TAX: Full-value property-tax rate per 10,000 dollars
  • PTRATIO: Pupil-teacher ratio by town
  • LSTAT: % lower status of the population
  • MEDV: Median value of owner-occupied homes in 1000 dollars

def histogram_boxplot(data, feature, figsize=(8,1.5), kde=True,color=None):
    fig, (ax_box, ax_hist) = plt.subplots(2, sharex=True, gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": [0.25, 0.75]}, figsize=figsize)

    sns.histplot(data=data, x=feature, kde=kde, ax=ax_hist,color=color)
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box, showmeans=True,color=color)

    # Remove the boxplot x labels
    ax_box.set_xlabel('')

    #removing space between plots
    plt.subplots_adjust(hspace=0)

#function that creates scatterplots for high and low corrs
def high_corr_scatterplots2(df, high=0.7, low=-0.7):

  corr_matrix = df.corr().round(2)
  #getting column and row names where they arent the same and if they are between high and low corrs
  high_corr_pairs = [(feat1, feat2) for feat1 in df.columns for feat2 in df.columns
                      if feat1 != feat2 and (corr_matrix.loc[feat1, feat2] >= high or corr_matrix.loc[feat1, feat2] <= low)]

  #creating a set to drop pair duplicates then plotting scatterplot for each pair.
  unique_pairs = set(tuple(sorted(pair)) for pair in high_corr_pairs)
  for feature1, feature2 in unique_pairs:
      plt.figure(figsize=(5,5))
      sns.scatterplot(data=df, x=feature1, y=feature2, color='blue');
      plt.title(f'{feature1} and {feature2}');
      plt.show()

Let's also look into MEDV and RM as there are outliers that may throw off a linear model. Because RM is one of the higher correlated fields to our target, MEDV, we will attempt to visually 'winsorize' the extreme points by moving them closer to the next highest points so they will not throw off the model completely and we still will retain noise.

Data Preprocessing¶

Looking at our label, MEDV, we can see that there are several points that may be of concern for a linear model. We will attempt to visually winsorize the points by bringing them closer to the next extreme value near them. That way we can keep noise as well as not throw off our model.

#function for vif
def vif(xtrain):
    vifdf = pd.DataFrame()
    vifdf["feature"] = xtrain.columns
    # finding vif for each column
    vifdf["VIF"] = [variance_inflation_factor(xtrain.values, i) for i in range(xtrain.shape[1])]
    return vifdf

Checking Linear Regression Assumptions¶

Heteroscedasticity test¶

The GoldfeldQuandt test is a common way to test for Heteroscedasticity.

In [ ]:
#performing goldfeldquandt test for heteroscedasticity
gq = sms.het_goldfeldquandt(y_train, X_train)

# Access the test statistics and p-value
p_value = gq[1]

print(f"P-value: {np.round(p_value,4)}")

P-value: 0.4853

We can see that the P-value is .4177. which is greater than the 0.05 needed to reject the null hypothesis, therefore we cannot assume that heteroscedasticity is present.

Residual Mean + Normality¶

In [ ]:
#defining residuals
residuals = ols_model.resid

#creating plot
ax = sns.histplot(residuals,kde=True);
ax.set_xlabel("Predictions", fontsize=14)
ax.set_ylabel("Residuals", fontsize=14)
ax.set_title(f'Residuals (average: {np.mean(residuals)})',fontsize=16);

The average of the residuals is very close to zero and the residuals appear to be normally distributed.

Linearity¶

We can see that there isn't a clear shape or pattern suggesting that fit values and residuals are linearly correlated.

Overall, the model seems to check the boxes of linear regression assumptions.

Training set results

In [ ]:
actual = y_train
predicted = ols_model.predict(X_train)

mae = np.mean(np.abs(actual - predicted))
rmse = np.sqrt(((actual - predicted) ** 2).mean())
mape = np.mean(np.abs((actual - predicted)) / actual) * 100

print("MAE:", np.round(mae,5))
print("RMSE:", np.round(rmse,5))
print("MAPE:", np.round(mape,5))

Test set results

In [ ]:
actual = y_test

mae = np.mean(np.abs(actual - predicted))
rmse = np.sqrt(((actual - predicted) ** 2).mean())
mape = np.mean(np.abs((actual - predicted)) / actual) * 100

print("MAE:", np.round(mae,5))
print("RMSE:", np.round(rmse,5))
print("MAPE:", np.round(mape,5))

Actionable Insights and Recommendations¶

-Housing in value in Boston appears to be driven mostly by avg number of rooms and vicinity to 'lower status people'. Many of the other features are in the dataset are essentially meaningless to creating a predictive model.

-an increase in value with an increase in rooms seems reasonble and interepretable, however LSTAT seems to be subjective.

-Some of the data appears to be capped, such as MEDV at 50.

-Our model checks the boxes for linear assumptions and performed decently.

-Potentially with a more a complex model or different features a better result can be found.
